To access help documentation inside the IEx:

h {MODULE_NAME}.{FUNCTION_NAME}

For example,

iex(1)> h Enum.count

This can really come in handy when you're working offline and you need
to see how to use a particular function from a module along with examples.
%
How to color elixir logs?

require Logger

# To add color to log text
Logger.info("Elixirforum", ansi_color: :yellow)

# To add highlight / background color
Logger.info("Elixirforum", ansi_color: :magenta_background)

# To add text color and background color
Logger.info("Elixirforum", ansi_color: [:yellow, :magenta_background])

Source  : https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Nc4_DQyerwg
Channel : https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCiTNXma-lzM6XjhgPQzKREg
%
What is the difference between .ex and .exs files in an elixir project?

.ex files are compiled and written to disk, whereas the .exs files are
compiled and executed in memory, also they are not written to disk.
%
To know more about the data type of an elixir term,

(Assuming you're inside an active IEx shell)

iex(1)> i 2
Term
  2
Data type
  Integer
Reference modules
  Integer
Implemented protocols
  IEx.Info, Inspect, List.Chars, String.Chars
%
You're into serious debugging, scattering IO.inspects all over the place,
suddenly you realize, it's not printing the full term and ends with a `...`.
IO.inspect has an option, that can save you!

IO.inspect(ANY_BIG_BLAH_BLAH, limit: :infinity)

Adding the [limit: :infinity] will print all of the term to the console.

To learn more about IO.inspect Options, type `h Inspect.Opts`.
